rs talk about comparative literature in Asia, they tend to focus on translation between European languages and Chinese, Korean, and Japanese, as practiced since about 1900. In contrast, Saussy focuses on the period before 1850, when the translation of foreign works into Chinese was rare because Chinese literary tradition overshadowed those around it.The Making of Barbarians looks closely at literary works that were translated into Chinese from foreign languages or resulted from contact with alien peoples. The book explores why translation was such an undervalued practice in premodern China, and how this vast and prestigious culture dealt with those outside it before a new group of foreigners—Europeans—appeared on the horizon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh  aAbsurdity.  aAesthetic Theory.  aAlien language.  aAn Lushan Rebellion.  aAnalects.  aAnyang.  aApprenticeship.  aArchaeology.  aArchaism.  aBarbarian.  aBarbarism (linguistics).  aBehavior.  aBuddhism.  aCentral Asia.  aChinese characters.  aChinese culture.  aCollecting.  aConfucianism.  aConspiracy theory.  aCritical theory.  aCriticism.  aCultural assimilation.  aCultural imperialism.  aCustomer.  aDissociative identity disorder.  aDu Fu.  aEditing.  aEpithet.  aEthnocentrism.  aEthnography.  aForeign language.  aGansu.  aGoguryeo.  aGrammar.  aGuan Yu.  aHan Yu.  aHermeneutics.  aHistoriography.  aHunan.  aIdeology.  aImport.  aJi Yun.  aJurchen people.  aLinguistic imperialism.  aLiterature.  aManchuria.  aMencius.  aMilitary campaign.  aMilitary dictatorship.  aMongols.  aNigerians.  aNorth–South divide.  aOirats.  aPeire Vidal.  aPoetry.  aPolemic.  aPrecedent.  aPrejudice.  aPronunciation.  a